div.div:
This is a useful way to represent a trained network (with sample value states) because it shows a clear trajectory between initial attribute values (vector passed in), interim attribute values (attributes pooled into other attributes, just like attributes accrete into types), and the functions used to aggregate them.
It removes the idea of neuron input/output trajectory (from start to final value) having a unique meaning, which implies the ideas of data augmentation & of similar data having different positions, rather than neuron layer trajectory (relationship between values in different layers) having meaning.

div.div: How would you generate this representation as a good explainer of the neural network idea?
It simplifies the neural network to important interfaces (value state) while permuting the object in that interface (value) to be in a recognizable format (vector they fed into the network).
- recognizable terms for the audience (semantic map)
- identifies the right structures to represent key concepts
- retains the information about the object that is necessary to connect the representation with the original form (keeping function links between nodes)
- keeps the representation mappable to the original neural network: the overall shape & position of attributes is the same, although some attributes are missing or are filled in with values
